# Admin data

Name accelsearch

Usage "Search an FFT or short time series for pulsars using a Fourier domain acceleration search with harmonic summing."

Version [exec date +%d%b%y]

Commandline full_cmd_line

# Options (in order you want them to appear)

Int -ncpus   ncpus      {Number of processors to use with OpenMP} \
	-r 1 oo  -d 1
Int -lobin   lobin      {The first Fourier frequency in the data file} \
	-r 0 oo  -d 0
Int -numharm numharm    {The number of harmonics to sum (power-of-two)}\
	-r 1 32 -d 8
Int -zmax    zmax       {The max (+ and -) Fourier freq deriv to search} \
	-r 0 1200  -d 200
Int -wmax    wmax       {The max (+ and -) Fourier freq double derivs to search} \
	-r 0 4000
Float -sigma sigma      {Cutoff sigma for choosing candidates}\
	-r 1.0 30.0 -d 2.0
Double -rlo     rlo     {The lowest Fourier frequency (of the highest harmonic!) to search} \
	-r 0.0 oo
Double -rhi     rhi     {The highest Fourier frequency (of the highest harmonic!) to search} \
	-r 0.0 oo
Double -flo     flo     {The lowest frequency (Hz) (of the highest harmonic!) to search} \
	-r 0.0 oo -d 1.0
Double -fhi     fhi     {The highest frequency (Hz) (of the highest harmonic!) to search} \
	-r 0.0 oo -d 10000.0
Flag   -inmem   inmem   {Compute full f-fdot plane in memory.  Very fast, but only for short time series.}
Flag   -photon  photon  {Data is poissonian so use freq 0 as power normalization}
Flag   -median  median  {Use block-median power normalization (default)}
Flag   -locpow  locpow  {Use double-tophat local-power normalization (not usually recommended)}
String  -zaplist    zaplist \
        {A file of freqs+widths to zap from the FFT (only if the input file is a *.[s]dat file)}
Double  -baryv      baryv \
        {The radial velocity component (v/c) towards the target during the obs} \
        -r -0.1 0.1  -d 0.0
Flag   -otheropt otheropt  {Use the alternative optimization (for testing/debugging)}
Flag   -noharmpolish noharmpolish  {Do not use 'harmpolish' by default}
Flag   -noharmremove noharmremove  {Do not remove harmonically related candidates (never removed for numharm = 1)}

# Rest of command line:

Rest infile {Input file name(s) of the floating point .fft or .[s]dat file(s).  '.inf' file(s) of the same name must also exist} \
        -c 1 16384

Description {accelsearch searches a Fourier power spectrum
.RB ( .fft ,
normally produced by
.BR realfft (1))
or a short time series
.RB ( .dat / .sdat )
for pulsar signals, using a Fourier-domain acceleration search with
harmonic summing.  At each candidate frequency it searches a range of
constant Fourier-frequency derivatives
.RB ( -zmax ,
approximating a constant acceleration during the observation) and,
optionally, constant second derivatives
.RB ( -wmax ,
approximating a constant jerk), summing
.B -numharm
harmonics (a power of two, up to 32) at each trial to improve
sensitivity to narrow pulsar signals.  Larger
.B -zmax
and
.B -wmax
searches find more strongly accelerated or jerking binaries (e.g.
pulsars with massive companions) at the cost of a much larger search
volume and run time; the PRESTO FAQ has guidance on reasonable ranges
for various companion masses and orbital periods.
.PP
The Fourier-domain acceleration search technique implemented here is
described in Ransom, Eikenberry, & Middleditch (2002),
https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2002AJ....124.1788R/abstract, and
the jerk-search extension
.RB ( -wmax )
is described in Andersen & Ransom (2018),
https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018ApJ...863L..13A/abstract.  If
accelsearch contributes to a publication, please cite the relevant
paper(s) (see also CITATION.cff in the PRESTO repository).
.PP
Candidates above
.B -sigma
(the equivalent Gaussian significance, corrected for the number of
independent frequencies and derivatives searched in this run) are
written to a
.I .cand
text summary and a binary
.I _ACCEL_<zmax>
(or
.I _ACCEL_<zmax>_JERK_<wmax>
when
.B -wmax
is used) candidate file for later sifting (e.g. with
.IR ACCEL_sift.py )
and folding with
.BR prepfold (1).
.B -inmem
computes the full f/fdot plane in memory instead of incrementally,
which is much faster but only practical for short time series.  When
searching a
.I .dat/.sdat
time series directly (rather than a pre-computed
.IR .fft ),
.B -zaplist
removes known interference frequencies from the internally-computed
FFT before the search runs, without a separate
.BR zapbirds (1)
pass; in that case (and only in that case)
.B -baryv
should be given if the time series was barycentered, so that the
zapped birdie frequencies (known in the topocentric frame) are
shifted correctly before zapping.
.PP
.B -ncpus
sets the number of OpenMP threads used to parallelize the search.
accelsearch is one of the few PRESTO routines where multiple CPUs
give a substantial speedup (the others being
.BR rfifind (1)
and
.BR prepfold_multi (1));
most of the rest of PRESTO is effectively single-threaded, with
parallelism instead coming from running independent searches (e.g.
different DM trials) concurrently.
.PP
Example: a zmax=200 acceleration search of a barycentered time series'
FFT, summing up to 8 harmonics:
.RS
.nf
realfft mypulsar_DM10.00.dat
accelsearch -zmax 200 -numharm 8 mypulsar_DM10.00.fft
.fi
.RE
}

Author {Scott Ransom <sransom@nrao.edu>}

SeeAlso {prepdata(1), prepsubband(1), realfft(1), zapbirds(1), prepfold(1), rfifind(1), prepfold_multi(1)}
